Vice-President Samia Suluhu Hassan is scheduled to officially unveil the 13-member team tomorrow, according to the Minister in Vice-President s Office, Union Affairs and Environment, Mr January Makamba.He said the team is tasked to undertake immediate steps and develop innovative strategies to address the situation. The task force will submit its report to the Vice-President next month, recommending on the best ways to manage the environment in the Great Ruaha River and sustainably use its water, said the minister.Mr Makamba cited human activities, including agriculture and fishery as the main factors for environmental degradation in the Great Ruaha River which supplies 22 per cent of the Rufiji catchment system s total flow. About 80 per cent of hydroelectric power generation in the country depends on Ruaha River basin as it flows to Kidatu and Mtera dams, he observed.The minister noted that the decreased flows have been recorded since the 1990s, with complete drying of the sections of the River in 1993.Mr Makamba mentioned the task force members as Director of Coordination and Policies in the President s Office, Regional Administration and Local Government, Dr Andrew Komba, Director of Environment, Mr Richard Muyungi and Engineer Seth Lusemwa from the Ministry of Water and Irrigation.Others are acting Director General of the National Land Use Planning Commission, Dr Stephen Nindi, Land Commissioner Mary Makondo, Rufiji River Basin Board Director Idris Msuya, Njombe Regional Administrative Secretary Jackson Saitabau and Iringa Regional Administrative Secretary Wamoja Dickolagwa.